oakcurric:unit-511
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Medieval women: what can we learn from Matilda about women in medieval England?"@en ;
  curric:slug "medieval-women-what-can-we-learn-from-matilda-about-women-in-medieval-england" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils analyse the historical significance of Empress Matilda's
  life. They use her life as a lens to consider the lives of noble women in medieval
  England."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on various units from across key stages 1-3 that
  feature medieval rulers and women in positions of power and influence. Having studied figures
  such as Boudica, Aethelflaed and Nūr Jahān pupils will be prepared for this depth study of a
  powerful female figure in the medieval period. This unit prepares pupils for future year 7
  units about medieval England, providing a layer of knowledge about medieval society and
  politics that will allow them to understand future developments more easily.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-511-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-511-2 ;
  curric:id "511"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.407981Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-525
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "European conquest of the Americas: why was its impact so devastating?"@en ;
  curric:slug "european-conquest-of-the-americas-why-was-its-impact-so-devastating" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the Americas before the arrival of Europeans
  before examining the impact of their early settlement and colonisation, with a particular
  focus on England's first successful American colonies."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of non-European societies
  built throughout key stages 2 and 3. This unit prepares pupils for all future units that
  reference the Atlantic world from the 16th century onwards, including studies of the
  Transatlantic Slave Trade, Haiti, the British Empire and eventually decolonisation.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-525-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-525-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-525-3 ;
  curric:id "525"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.473516Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oakcurric:unit-527
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Transatlantic Slavery: how were West African societies impacted?"@en ;
  curric:slug "transatlantic-slavery-how-were-west-african-societies-impacted" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the kingdoms of the Sahel and how the arrival of
  European traders in the region began to destabilise West Africa. Pupils build a deep
  knowledge of Transatlantic Slavery whilst retaining a focus on the impacts it had in West
  Africa."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of the way in which
  European powers interacted with the indigenous peoples of the Americas that they built in the
  earlier unit on this topic. It also makes use of pupils' knowledge of West African
  civilisations such as Benin and Mali that they developed in key stage 2 and year 7 units.
  This unit prepares pupils for multiple future key stage 3 units that reference Britain's
  involvement in the Transatlantic Slave Trade, such as those about the British Empire and
  decolonisation.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-527-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-527-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-527-3 ;
  curric:id "527"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.506396Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oakcurric:unit-524
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Life in Tudor England: was there a 'Golden Age' for the poor?"@en ;
  curric:slug "life-in-tudor-england-was-there-a-golden-age-for-the-poor" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils assess the extent to which Elizabethan England represented a
  'Golden Age' for the poor. They examine the causes of poverty in this period and learn
  about contemporary responses to this growing problem before evaluating whether things
  improved for this group."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of Elizabeth I's reign
  that they developed in the previous unit and their knowledge of the medieval poor built in
  the unit on medieval Norwich. This unit prepares pupils for later studies of ordinary lives
  and the poor, such as the year 8 unit examining whether industrialisation revolutionised
  people's lives.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-524-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-524-2 ;
  curric:id "524"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.710202Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-521
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Henry VIII and the Reformation: how unusual was the English Reformation?"@en ;
  curric:slug "henry-viii-and-the-reformation-how-unusual-was-the-english-reformation" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the European Reformation and its influence on
  Henry VIII's break with Rome. In doing so, pupils compare the English Reformation to the
  ones experienced on the continent."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the previous unit about the Renaissance,
  enriching pupils' understanding of this key period in European and British history. It also
  builds on pupils' knowledge of late medieval England that they developed in the unit about
  the Wars of the Roses. This unit prepares pupils for the next two units by providing a
  coherent backdrop to the events of Elizabeth I's reign.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-521-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-521-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-521-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-521-4 ;
  curric:id "521"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.731468Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-526
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The English Civil War: what can pamphlets tell us about 17th century politics?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-english-civil-war-what-can-pamphlets-tell-us-about-17th-century-politics" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils briefly learn about the causes and conduct of the English
  Civil War. They then learn about Oliver Cromwell's rule and the restoration of the
  monarchy. Pupils finish the unit by examining how these events were represented in popular
  political pamphlets of the day."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils’ knowledge of Tudor England that they
  developed in two units about the reign of Elizabeth I. This unit prepares pupils for the one
  that follows it, where their knowledge of the English Civil War, interregnum and restoration
  all provide a comprehensive schema for learning about the events of the Glorious Revolution.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-526-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-526-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-526-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-526-4 ;
  curric:id "526"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.802083Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-530
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The East India Company: when did Mughal authority collapse?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-east-india-company-when-did-mughal-authority-collapse" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the arrival of the East India Company on the
  fringes of the Mughal Empire. They examine how the East India Company's power and
  influence grew, and how they, along with various Indian rulers, destabilised Mughal power
  over India."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds directly on pupils' knowledge and understanding
  of the character of the Mughal Empire in India that they built two units before this. This
  unit prepares pupils for the later year 9 unit that focuses on the transformation of the
  British Empire.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-530-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-530-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-530-3 ;
  curric:id "530"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.823408Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oakcurric:unit-1078
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Black Death and the Silk Road: how connected was the medieval world?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-black-death-and-the-silk-roads-how-connected-was-the-medieval-world" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils analyse the connections that existed in the medieval world by
  looking at the transmission and impact of the Black Death. They learn about its spread
  across the Silk Roads and in doing so develop their understanding of how trade and
  communication connected the medieval world."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of various aspects of the
  medieval world that they have studied in key stages 2 and 3. It draws together what pupils
  have learnt about the geography and connected nature of the Islamic and Christian worlds of
  the Mediterranean, enriching this with additional understanding of the east. This unit
  prepares pupils for the next unit, which focuses directly on the long term impacts of the
  Black Death in England.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1078-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1078-2 ;
  curric:id "1078"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.874753Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-536
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The British Empire: how far was it transformed in the mid-nineteenth century?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-british-empire-how-far-was-it-transformed-in-the-mid-nineteenth-century" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about how the British Empire changed in the
  mid-nineteenth century. They examine the British Empire in India, Jamaica, East Asia, and
  Africa and evaluate the extent to which it was transformed during this period."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of empires more generally,
  built throughout key stages 1, 2 and 3, alongside what they have learnt about the British
  Empire specifically in both year 8 and 9 where the focus was on the Americas and India. This
  unit prepares pupils for both the next unit, about the commemoration and contestation of the
  Empire, and the later year 9 unit about decolonisation in the British Empire.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-536-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-536-2 ;
  curric:id "536"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.970071Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oakcurric:unit-522
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Elizabeth I: why has Elizabeth been represented so differently?"@en ;
  curric:slug "elizabeth-i-why-has-elizabeth-been-represented-so-differently" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about Elizabeth I's reign before examining some popular
  depictions of her. They build knowledge about her religious, domestic, and foreign
  policies before considering why she has been represented so differently."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of earlier Tudor monarchs
  and the religious change that took place during their reigns. It extends and enriches pupils'
  understanding of this dynasty that they built in the previous unit. It also introduces pupils
  to more historical interpretations, building on those that they have encountered already in
  key stages 2 and 3. This unit prepares pupils for the next unit, where Elizabeth's reign is
  viewed through a distinctly social lens, by providing a wider overview of some of the events
  of her reign.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-522-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-522-2 ;
  curric:id "522"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.983488Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-510
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Crusades: did Europeans go on crusade to capture the 'holy land'?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-crusades-did-europeans-go-on-crusade-to-capture-the-holy-land" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils develop a deep understanding of the First Crusade's
  background. They learn how the interplay of events across Western Europe, the Byzantine
  Empire, and the Seljuk Empire led to this significant campaign."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of the 11th century
  mediterranean world that they have developed so far in year 7, and in year 5 units about
  Islam and Baghdad. These ensure that pupils understand the holistic context to the crusade
  and are able to comprehend a wide range of causes for the crusade. This unit prepares pupils
  for later year 7 units that deal with medieval conflict where new examples enrich their
  understanding of this concept. It also helps to familiarise themselves with various locations
  that feature in the unit about the Black Death and the Silk Roads.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-510-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-510-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-510-3 ;
  curric:id "510"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.990382Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-warfare-and-conflict .

oakcurric:unit-508
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Norman Conquest: how do we know about the impact of the Conquest on England?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-norman-conquest-how-do-we-know-about-the-impact-of-the-conquest-on-england" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the causes and conduct of the Norman Conquest of
  England. They develop their understanding of the sorts of evidence historians use to make
  claims, and how they do this, building an understanding of how we know about these events."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils’ knowledge of Anglo-Saxon England that
  they developed across various year 5 and 6 units. Here, their knowledge and understanding of
  Anglo-Saxon society and culture underpins their ability to process the changes brought about
  by the Norman Conquest. This unit prepares pupils for future year 7 units that cover medieval
  England, including the next three in sequence, and for other key stage 3 units that maintain
  a conceptual focus on sources and evidence.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-508-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-508-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-508-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-508-4 ;
  curric:id "508"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.046837Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-invasion-migration-and-settlement .

oakcurric:unit-528
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Glorious Revolution: how do historians' views of it differ?"@en ;
  curric:slug "glorious-revolution-why-did-whig-historians-call-it-glorious-and-bloodless" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the Glorious Revolution and the way in which
  different historians have viewed it. They learn about the causes of this important event
  before examining Whig and revisionist arguments about its nature."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the previous unit, developing pupils'
  knowledge of 17th century England further. It also builds on pupils' knowledge of English
  parliamentary traditions that they first encountered in the year 7 unit about Magna Carta.
  This unit prepares pupils for future units about the Enlightenment, where some of the same
  political ideas are explored, and sets the scene for a focus on Britain and her empire which
  began to grow considerably after the events of the Glorious Revolution.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-528-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-528-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-528-3 ;
  curric:id "528"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.049018Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-534
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The French Revolution: How did Europe respond to the French Revolution?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-french-revolution-what-do-cartoons-tell-us-about-british-attitudes" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about British responses to the French Revolution and
  Napoleon's rise. They examine how revolutionary ideas spread to Ireland and end the unit
  by learning about the Napoleonic Wars and how this period was represented in political
  cartoons of the day."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge from the unit about the
  Enlightenment. It refers to and develops to Enlightenment thinking, charting the practical
  impact this had in France in the late eighteenth century. This unit prepares pupils for the
  next unit about the Haitian Revolution, where pupils' knowledge of eighteenth century
  political developments in France are key to understanding events in Haiti.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-534-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-534-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-534-3 ;
  curric:id "534"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.142349Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-520
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Renaissance: what do the artefacts of the Renaissance tell us about it?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-renaissance-what-do-the-artefacts-of-the-renaissance-tell-us-about-it" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the Renaissance by examining its material
  culture. They study various artefacts of the Renaissance and compare the Northern and
  Italian Renaissances. Throughout, pupils reflect on what evidence about the Renaissance
  can be taken from these sources."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on previous units where pupils have looked at
  evidence and material culture, such as in year 5 and 6 when studying the Anglo-Saxons and
  Vikings. This unit prepares pupils for the next unit, which covers the Reformation, by
  prefacing religious change with the study of cultural change. It also prepares pupils for any
  further study of material culture, sources and evidence.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-520-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-520-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-520-3 ;
  curric:id "520"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.154061Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-545
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Thematic study: how has the role of women in British society changed?"@en ;
  curric:slug "thematic-study-how-has-the-role-of-women-in-british-society-changed" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils consolidate and extend their knowledge of history before 1066
  by examining how women's roles in British society have changed from the medieval period to
  the present."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on multiple key stage 1, 2 and 3 units that have
  discussed the role and position of women. This unit prepares pupils for other thematic
  studies in key stage 4, where the focus is also on following a specific idea or theme across
  a broad expanse of time.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-545-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-545-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-545-3 ;
  curric:id "545"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.302573Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-519
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Wars of the Roses: what does it tell us about fifteenth-century England?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-wars-of-the-roses-what-does-it-tell-us-about-fifteenth-century-england" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils develop an understanding of the events of the period known as
  the Wars of the Roses. In doing so, they analyse the reasons for instability during this
  period, reflecting on what the Wars of the Roses can tell us about fifteenth-century
  England."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge and understanding of
  sources of medieval instability that they developed in the previous unit. This unit prepares
  pupils for their study of the Tudor period by contextualising Henry VIII's desire to restore
  monarchical power following the events of this unit.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-519-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-519-2 ;
  curric:id "519"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.367606Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-warfare-and-conflict .

oakcurric:unit-1151
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The British Empire: why did it grow in the 17th and 18th centuries?"@en ;
  curric:slug "commonwealth-and-restoration-why-did-the-republican-experiment-fail" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils develop overview knowledge of why the British Empire grew in
  the 17th and 18th centuries. They learn about the state of Britain's empire at the
  beginning and end of the 'long eighteenth century' before analysing differing historians'
  arguments about why it grew."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on previous key stage 3 units that introduced
  Britain's relationship to the Americas, its involvement in slavery and the political changes
  that had taken place in Britain by 1688. This unit prepares pupils for future in-depth key
  stage 3 units that focus on the growth, transformation and eventual decline of Britain's
  empire.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1151-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1151-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1151-3 ;
  curric:id "1151"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.439947Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance ,
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-937
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Christian Church: how completely did the Great Schism transform Christendom?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-christian-church-how-completely-did-the-great-schism-transform-christendom" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the Great Schism. They study the similarities and
  differences between the Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox Churches and consider the
  degree to which the Great Schism fundamentally changed the relationship between these two
  centres of Christendom."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of the history of
  Christianity that they developed in years 4 and 5, enriching their understanding of the
  differing Christian traditions that they have previously encountered. This unit prepares
  pupils for the future year 7 unit on the First Crusade, providing vital context so that
  pupils understand the relationship between the Eastern and Western Christian Churches.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-937-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-937-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-937-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-937-4 ;
  curric:id "937"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.476883Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-538
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Women's suffrage: why did it take so long for women to get the vote in Britain?"@en ;
  curric:slug "womens-suffrage-what-do-sources-tell-us-about-womens-struggle-for-equality" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils analyse why it took so long for women to win the vote in
  Britain. They learn about the position of women in the early twentieth century, the
  campaigns for suffrage and the government's responses to these campaigns and women's
  contributions during the Great War."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge about protest and the
  franchise that they developed in the key stage 1 unit about Paul Stephenson and Emily
  Davison, and the earlier year 9 unit about the extension of the franchise. This unit prepares
  pupils for the later year 9 units about post-war Britain and the changing position of women
  in society.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-538-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-538-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-538-3 ;
  curric:id "538"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.508185Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-515
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Local history: how similar were medieval lives in Norwich?"@en ;
  curric:slug "local-history-how-similar-were-medieval-lives-in-norwich" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the similarities and differences between various
  medieval lives in Norwich. In doing so, they build deep knowledge of one particular
  historical place and what it tells us about medieval England more generally."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' key stage 2 knowledge of life during
  different periods like the Anglo-Saxon and Viking ages. It enriches their understanding of
  similarity and difference. It prepares pupils for the next unit as a point of comparison
  between life in Norwich and the medieval kingdom of Mali. It also prepares pupils for future
  year 7 units that deal with medieval culture and society, such as those about the Black Death
  and the Peasants' Revolt.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-515-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-515-2 ;
  curric:id "515"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.557115Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-529
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Mughal Empire: how important was violence to the Mughal conquests in India?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-mughal-empire-how-important-was-violence-to-the-mughal-conquests-in-india" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the foundation of the Mughal Empire, early Mughal
  rule and the way in which this had developed by the late 17th century. They end the unit
  by reflecting on the role played by violence during the expansion of Mughal rule in India."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' key stage 2 knowledge of a different
  and earlier Islamic empire when they focused on early Islamic civilisation and Baghdad. This
  unit prepares pupils for the forthcoming unit about the collapse of Mughal authority in India
  and its replacement by British East India Company rule.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-529-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-529-2 ;
  curric:id "529"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.630655Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oakcurric:unit-512
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "England under Henry II: how successfully did Henry reassert royal authority?"@en ;
  curric:slug "england-under-henry-ii-how-successfully-did-henry-reassert-royal-authority" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about England and the Angevin Empire under Henry II's
  rule. They then use their knowledge of Henry's rule to evaluate the degree to which he was
  a successful king."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on units from key stage 1 and 2 that have
  previously introduced pupils to other empires like those of Rome and Britain. It also
  develops pupils' knowledge and understanding of medieval England that they have built in
  previous units about the First Crusade and the Empress Matilda. This unit prepares pupils for
  the next unit, contextualising John's problems against Henry's successes, and provides
  further political context for the later unit on Edward I.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-512-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-512-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-512-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-512-4 ;
  curric:id "512"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.661663Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-1077
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The emergence of cabinet government: why did Walpole become Prime Minister?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-emergence-of-cabinet-government-why-did-walpole-become-prime-minister" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this short unit, pupils learn about the Hanoverian Succession and the emergence
  of Robert Walpole as Britain's first Prime Minister. They also develop an appreciation of
  how cabinet government was formed during this period."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on all previous units from key stages 1, 2 and 3
  where parliamentary traditions, government and methods of ruling were discussed. This unit
  prepares pupils to understand later changes to the British parliamentary system when they
  learn about the widening franchise in the 19th century and the fight for female suffrage in
  Victorian and Edwardian Britain.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1077-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1077-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1077-3 ;
  curric:id "1077"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.910663Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-517
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Peasants' Revolt: why do historians disagree about its causes?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-peasants-revolt-why-do-historians-disagree-about-its-causes" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the differing interpretations that exist
  regarding the causes of the Peasants' Revolt. They will examine the impact of the Black
  Death on England alongside the short-term causes of the uprising."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the previous unit, enriching pupils'
  knowledge of the impacts of the Black Death with a longer term focus in the English context.
  It also develops pupils' understanding of the sources of power in medieval England that they
  built in earlier year 7 units. This unit prepares pupils for the next one, where pupils look
  at further instability in medieval England.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-517-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-517-2 ;
  curric:id "517"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.031765Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-516
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Medieval West Africa: why was medieval Mali so successful?"@en ;
  curric:slug "medieval-west-africa-why-was-medieval-mali-so-successful" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the success of medieval Mali, with a focus on the
  second-order concept of causation. They build knowledge of the West African landscape and
  the role it played in Mali's rise. They will also learn about the rise of Islam in the
  region and Mansa Musa's pilgrimage."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of non-European
  civilisations and societies that they developed in key stages 1 and 2. It also develops their
  year 5 and 7 knowledge about the spread of Islam. If they studied Benin, this unit provides
  an additional West African reference point for their future study of the region. This unit
  prepares pupils for the next unit, as it outlines various trade connections that are
  revisited. It also prepares pupils for the year 8 unit about how West African societies were
  impacted by the Transatlantic Slave Trade.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-516-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-516-2 ;
  curric:id "516"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.180775Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-544
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Post-war Britain: for whom did the United Kingdom become a 'New Jerusalem'?"@en ;
  curric:slug "post-war-britain-for-whom-did-the-united-kingdom-become-a-new-jerusalem" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the significant changes that took place in
  post-war Britain: the establishment of the NHS and the welfare state, the growth of social
  democracy, the changing role of women and the experience of racism in Britain."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on any units pupils have studied in key stage 2
  and 3 that concern the Second World War and its impact on Britain and her empire. It also
  develops pupils' knowledge and understanding of social, economic and political change in
  Britain that they have built in key stage 3 units about the franchise and suffrage. This
  unit's lesson about women and their status prepares pupils for the next unit which focuses on
  the position of women in British society over time.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-544-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-544-2 ;
  curric:id "544"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.254509Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-invasion-migration-and-settlement .

oakcurric:unit-540
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Russian Revolution: did communism completely transform Russian society?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-russian-revolution-did-communism-completely-transform-russian-society" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about Karl Marx's theories regarding communism and the
  conduct and impact of the Bolshevik Revolution in 1917. They examine the Russian Civil War
  and Russian society in the 1920s and 30s, allowing them to judge the extent to which
  communism changed Russia."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the previous unit which focused on the First
  World War. It also builds on all units where pupils have developed knowledge about
  government, protest and democracy, which occur across key stages 1, 2 and 3. This unit
  prepares pupils for the following unit to give context to the role of the USSR in World War
  Two, but also provides necessary context for key stage 4 units about the Cold War, where
  again the USSR features heavily and the ideology of communism is referenced.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-540-1 ;
  curric:id "540"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.285943Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-514
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Edward I: What stopped Edward uniting all of Britain?"@en ;
  curric:slug "edward-is-conquests-what-stopped-unification-of-the-british-isles" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about Edward I's campaign to conquer Wales and Scotland
  and bring both under English rule. They will analyse the reasons why Edward was unable to
  achieve his aim."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of medieval politics in
  Britain and Europe that they developed in previous key stage 3 units about Henry II and Magna
  Carta. It enriches pupils' existing understanding of England's relationship with her
  neighbours that was first developed in key stage 1. This unit prepares pupils for future
  units when the separate nature of England and Scotland is referenced.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-514-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-514-2 ;
  curric:id "514"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.687579Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-535
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Industrial Revolution: did industrialisation revolutionise people's lives?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-industrial-revolution-did-industrialisation-revolutionise-peoples-lives" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the changes to life brought about by the
  Agricultural and Industrial Revolutions. They learn about calls for political reform and
  how this led to the 1832 Great Reform Act. Pupils end the unit by considering how much the
  Industrial Revolution changed people's lives."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on various year 8 and 9 units that have helped
  pupils to develop an understanding of eighteenth century events concerning Britain, her
  empire, and the Atlantic World. It also builds on the more superficial knowledge of Victoria
  Britain that pupils established in key stage 1. This unit prepares pupils for future units
  that examine political and imperial developments taking place during the same period, such as
  the extension of the franchise and the transformation of the British Empire.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-535-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-535-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-535-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-535-4 ;
  curric:id "535"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.717940Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-541
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "WW2: which events turned the tide in the story of the Second World War?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-second-world-war-which-event-turned-the-tide-of-the-second-world-war" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the rise of fascism in Europe and how this helped
  to bring about the Second World War. They examine key turning points in the conflict,
  including the Battle of Britain, the siege of Stalingrad, the D-Day landings and the use
  of atomic weapons in 1945."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on all previous units that focused on war and
  conflict, but in particular the key stage 2 units about the impact of the Second World War,
  and those units concerning the First World War that were presented in key stages 2 and 3.
  This unit prepares pupils for the next unit, where a working knowledge of the events of the
  war are important to contextualise the Holocaust, and also prepares pupils for key stage 4
  units about the Cold War.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-541-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-541-2 ;
  curric:id "541"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.719789Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-warfare-and-conflict .

oakcurric:unit-542
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Holocaust: what was the Holocaust?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-holocaust-what-was-the-holocaust" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils investigate what the Holocaust was. They place this
  significant event in context, examine Jewish life in Europe before WW2 and analyse Nazi
  persecution of the Jewish people. They also reflect on Jewish resistance and the role of
  various perpetrators in this event."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the previous unit about the Second World War.
  This unit prepares pupils for key stage 4 study of Nazi Germany, as well as for key stage 4
  migration units that discuss the historical treatment of Jews before the events of the
  Holocaust.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-542-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-542-2 ;
  curric:id "542"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.848046Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oakcurric:unit-531
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Enlightenment: what was the Enlightenment?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-enlightenment-what-was-the-enlightenment" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the Enlightenment and its impact on America,
  France, and the Atlantic World. They develop knowledge of the Enlightenment's background
  and ideas and consider its links to the 'Age of Revolution'."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of the ways in which ideas
  have challenged rulers and sources of power that they have developed across various units in
  key stage 1, 2 and 3. It also builds on pupils' knowledge of Europe's relationship with the
  Americas, developed in several earlier key stage 3 units. This unit prepares pupils for
  various future units that trace the impact of Enlightenment thought.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-531-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-531-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-531-3 ;
  curric:id "531"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.854353Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-533
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The Haitian Revolution: what was its role in the abolition of the slave trade?"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-haitian-revolution-what-was-its-role-in-the-abolition-of-the-slave-trade" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the causes and conduct of the Haitian Revolution
  before reflecting on its role in the abolition of the British slave trade in 1807."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge and understanding of
  Enlightenment ideas that they built in the previous lesson, their knowledge of Transatlantic
  Slavery and their knowledge of events in France during the revolutionary period of the late
  eighteenth century. This unit prepares pupils for later year 9 units that look at the
  experiences of decolonisation in the British Empire, providing a clear comparison with those
  events.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-533-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-533-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-533-3 ;
  curric:id "533"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.862461Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oakcurric:unit-938
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "11th-century Islamic worlds: how similar were the regions of the Islamic world?"@en ;
  curric:slug "11th-century-islamic-worlds-how-similar-were-the-regions-of-the-islamic-world" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils develop their knowledge and understanding of the Islamic
  world in the 11th century. Pupils study three connected, but contrasting, centres of
  Islamic civilisation: Baghdad, Cordoba and Sicily."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' year 5 knowledge of early Islamic
  civilisation. It deepens their understanding of Baghdad and how the politics of the Islamic
  world had changed since the 8th and 9th centuries. This unit prepares pupils for the future
  year 7 unit on the First Crusade, ensuring pupils can place that event within the context of
  changing Muslim rule.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-938-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-938-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-938-3 ;
  curric:id "938"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.865799Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-trade-ideas-and-communication .

oakcurric:unit-543
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Decolonisation: how similar was decolonisation throughout the British Empire?"@en ;
  curric:slug "decolonisation-how-similar-was-decolonisation-throughout-the-british-empire" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the similarities and differences between
  decolonisation in various parts of the British Empire. They examine this process in
  Ireland, India, Palestine, Africa and the Caribbean, providing them with ample knowledge
  to compare the experiences of each."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on all previous units that focused on the
  British Empire, and the concept of empire, that are spread across key stages 1, 2 and 3. This
  unit prepares pupils for the following unit where pupils' knowledge of imperial developments
  is complemented by an understanding of the social, economic and political changes that took
  place in Britain.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-543-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-543-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-543-3 ;
  curric:id "543"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.867733Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oakcurric:unit-513
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Magna Carta: how did Magna Carta survive?"@en ;
  curric:slug "king-john-and-magna-carta-why-was-magna-carta-revived" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the causes of the Magna Carta, its reissue and
  its continued importance in the development of the first parliaments. At the same time,
  pupils analyse how and why the principles of the Magna Carta survived."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' recently developed year 7 knowledge
  of medieval England, alongside their understanding of ideas such as government, rulers and
  ruling that they began to build in key stages 1 and 2 across a variety of people, places and
  times. This unit prepares pupils for various year 7 units that require an understanding of
  England's early parliaments and the legacies of Magna Carta, such as in units on the
  Peasants' Revolt and the Wars of the Roses.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-513-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-513-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-513-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-513-4 ;
  curric:id "513"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.871683Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

oakcurric:unit-539
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "World War One: how 'total' was it for people in the British Empire?"@en ;
  curric:slug "world-war-one-how-total-was-it-for-people-in-the-british-empire" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the First World War through the lens of its
  imperial dimension. They analyse the reasons for the outbreak of war and assess how it
  affected Britain at home and abroad."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of the First World War that
  they developed in the key stage 2 unit about the effect of the war on local communities. It
  also rests heavily on knowledge built about Britain's empire that pupils built across
  multiple year 8 and 9 units. This unit prepares pupils for various year 9 units that build on
  their knowledge of the events of the conflict itself, such as the unit that follows after
  this one about revolutionary change in Russia.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-539-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-539-2 ;
  curric:id "539"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.877331Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-warfare-and-conflict .

oakcurric:unit-537
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Interpreting the British Empire: how has it been commemorated and contested?"@en ;
  curric:slug "interpreting-the-british-empire-how-has-it-been-commemorated-and-contested" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about how the British Empire was viewed in the late
  nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. They analyse how imperial anxiety, decline, and
  decolonisation have all led to changes in its historiography."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of the mid--nineteenth
  century British Empire that they developed in the previous unit. It also builds on knowledge
  of the earlier British Empire that pupils developed in units about Mughal India, the East
  India Company and the growth of the Empire in the 17th and 18th centuries. This unit prepares
  pupils for the later year 9 unit about 20th decolonisation in the British Empire in the 20th
  century.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-537-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-537-2 ;
  curric:id "537"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.879162Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-empire-persecution-and-resistance .

oakcurric:unit-1152
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Widening the franchise: who gained the right to vote?"@en ;
  curric:slug "widening-the-franchise-who-gained-the-right-to-vote" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about England and the Angevin Empire under Henry II's
  rule. They then use their knowledge of Henry's rule to evaluate the degree to which he was
  a successful king."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of Victorian Britain that
  they have developed in units in key stage 1 and in earlier year 9 units such as 'The
  Industrial Revolution: did industrialisation revolutionise people's lives?'. This unit
  prepares pupils for the later year 9 unit that focuses on women's suffrage.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1152-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1152-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1152-3 ;
  curric:id "1152"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.887669Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-history-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-power-government-and-religion .

