# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-barons-obey-their-monarchs-orders
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Barons must obey the their monarch's orders."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although this is true in theory, in reality the barons and their monarch
  worked as a partnership: the monarch relied upon the barons and if they weren't doing a
  good enough job, they could expect to lose the support of their barons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.084524Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-europeans-conquered-americas-easily-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Europeans conquered the Americas easily because they had better weapons and
  technology."""@en ;
  curric:correction """European diseases killed and weakened many Native Americans, undermining
  indigenous resistance to European conquest."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.084718Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-kingdoms-west-africa-saw-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All kingdoms in West Africa saw the same changes as a result of the
  Transatlantic Slave Trade."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Some kingdoms were weaker as a result of wars between kingdoms, others were
  weakened because of alliances and others continued to thrive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.084794Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-government-help-people-need
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The government is there to help people when they are in need."@en ;
  curric:correction """Throughout much of history, governments have regularly failed to support the
  most vulnerable in society, as many of them did not see that as their function."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085310Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-decide-themselves-religious-beliefs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "People decide for themselves what religious beliefs they hold."@en ;
  curric:correction """For much of English history, people had to believe what the monarch told them
  to believe, else they would be killed. This insistence upon belief became more relaxed
  only in the relatively recent past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085503Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-protestant-reformation-single-event
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Protestant Reformation was a single event."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Protestant Reformation happened over a long period of time and happened
  differently in different countries. Some countries moved swiftly away from Catholic
  beliefs, whereas in others the pace of change was slower or even reverted backwards."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-restored-monarchy-acted-exactly-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Restored monarchy acted exactly the same way as it had before the Civil
  War"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Charles II made a great effort to work with Parliament more co-operatively
  than his father. He let Parliament sit continuously for 18 years."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-europeans-powerful-other-states-social
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Europeans were more powerful than other states and social groups in the 17th
  century."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although European groups like the EIC were powerful, the Mughal Emperors
  retained greater power in the 17th century. Aurangzeb comprehensively defeated the EIC's
  military challenged during Child's War."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085823Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-silk-traded-along-silk-road
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only silk was traded along the Silk Road."@en ;
  curric:correction """Silk was a primary commodity for a long time along the Silk Road, but there
  were many different goods and ideas that were traded between East and West along the trade
  route."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086074Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-british-victory-opium-wars-allowed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """British victory in the Opium wars allowed it to conquer large areas of China
  and establish many new colonies."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Hong Kong was gained as a new British colony but Britain used its victory in
  the Opium Wars to force the Qing empire to change its behaviour, rather than to create new
  colonies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086378Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-eic-victory-battle-plassey-relied
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "EIC victory in the Battle of Plassey only relied upon its own strengths."@en ;
  curric:correction """The EIC army benefitted from Indian support, including its secret agreement
  with Mir Jafar who refused to let his troops participate in the battle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-america-discovered-europeans
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils think that America was ‘discovered’ by Europeans or that it was a 'new'
  place."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that there were long-established communities in the Americas
  before European arrival - they did not need to be discovered."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-english-navy-destroyed-spanish-armada
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The English navy destroyed the Spanish Armada."@en ;
  curric:correction """Most of the ships lost from the Spanish Armada were sunk in storms after the
  battle against the English navy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086433Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pope-powerful-person-roman-catholic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The pope has always been the most powerful person in the Roman Catholic
  Church."""@en ;
  curric:correction """For much of the medieval period, a power struggle between the pope and local
  kings took place for control of religion within each country. In the early medieval period
  the pope had very little power at all."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086470Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-elizabethan-period-golden-age
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Elizabethan period was a 'Golden Age'."@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst there were many positives that came about during the Elizabethan era,
  many people suffered from poverty and starvation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086657Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-church-physical-building
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might think that 'the Church' is a physical building in which people
  pray."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that 'the Church' refers to the wider organisation of the Christian
  faith, including all buildings and people which belong to it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086717Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-parliament-17th-century-similarly-superior
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Parliament in the 17th century was similarly superior to the monarch as it is
  today"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Parliament was there to assist the monarch but they could rule without it and
  did not consider it an equal to themselves"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086723Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-monarch-next-line-throne
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Only children of the monarch are next in line for the throne, not
  siblings."""@en ;
  curric:correction """As Charles II did not have any legitimate children, his heir was his brother,
  James II."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086731Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-contemporary-sources-accepted-based-solely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That all contemporary sources can be accepted based solely on the value of
  their content."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Historians must consider how the provenance of a source may have affected the
  way it discusses and portrays a historical issue."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086862Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-english-nation-animal-lovers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The English have always been a nation of animal lovers."@en ;
  curric:correction """Blood sports were a very popular form of entertainment for hundreds of years.
  A large variety of animals were killed for our entertainment, such as bulls, bears and
  badgers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-triangular-trade-simple-trading-route
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The triangular trade was a simple trading route with three main points."@en ;
  curric:correction """The triangular trade was a complex system of trade, that is often simplified
  to help us better understand it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087301Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-revolutionary-ideas-failed-spread-france
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Revolutionary ideas failed to spread from France to other European
  countries."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Revolutionary ideas did spread to other European countries, but they did not
  cause any successful revolutions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-dissection-banned-medieval
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think that dissection was banned by the medieval Catholic
  Church."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that, while dissection was not banned, there was still a
  taboo around handling dead bodies which limited the number of dissections that took place
  during the medieval period."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087471Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-whigs-gained-their-name-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The 'Whigs' gained their name because of the fancy wigs and hairstyles that
  were the fashion in the 17th and 18th centuries."""@en ;
  curric:correction """'Whigs' has nothing to do with hairstyles, but was instead originally a
  derogatory term used to describe the 'Country Party', as they were originally known.
  'Whig' was a sound Scottish drovers shouted when controlling cattle on the way to market."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087614Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-contemporary-british-thinkers-complete-supporters
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All contemporary British thinkers were complete supporters of the French
  Revolution."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Levels of support for the French Revolution amongst contemporary British
  thinkers varied."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087693Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-monarchs-need-secure-their-positions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Monarchs need to secure their positions by imprisoning or killing any
  claimants to the throne."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although many monarchs have acted in this way, there are countless examples
  of monarchs who tolerated the freedom of strong claimants to the throne in order to not
  appear despotic. William III of Orange is a good example."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088501Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-interpretations-history-set-stone
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Interpretations of history are set in stone."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many aspects of history face regular revisions as more research is
  conducted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088756Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-parts-british-empire-governed-directly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All parts of the British Empire were always governed directly by the British
  government."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In the first half of the 19th century, India was ruled by the British East
  India Company, not by the British Government."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088765Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-winning-right-vote-1919-led
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Winning the right to vote in 1919 led to a radical transformation in the
  status and position of women in society in the 1920s and 1930s."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although the Representation of the People Act of 1919 was a significant
  turning point, Britain in the 1920s and 1930s remained a very patriarchal society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-aurangzeb-completely-intolerant-towards-alienated
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Aurangzeb was completely intolerant towards and alienated all non-Muslims."@en ;
  curric:correction """Aurangzeb continued to support non-Muslim places of worship and to promote
  non-Muslim officials in the empire, leading to increased numbers of Hindus and Sikhs
  serving the Mughal Empire by the end of his reign."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088852Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-napoleon-ever-experienced-success-period
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Napoleon only ever experienced success during this period, and was never
  defeated."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Napoleon faced military setbacks (particularly at sea) during this period,
  usually at the hands of the British."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088860Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-wars-roses-ended
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think the Wars of the Roses ended with the victory of Henry VII
  at Bosworth and that all historians agree with this interpretation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that Henry VII also faced rebellions at the start of his reign and,
  although the Tudors are well-known for their rule of England, few expected them to last
  long as a result of the rebellions and the prior decades of instability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089154Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-equal-pay-act-1970-led
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Equal Pay Act (1970) led to women being paid the same as men."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although the Equal Pay Act made it illegal to pay women less than men for
  doing the same work, many employers adjusted job descriptions for female workers to avoid
  paying them equally."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089282Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-protestantism-single-unified-religion
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Protestantism is a single unified religion."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are, today, thousands of different Christian denominations that can be
  considered versions of Protestantism. Almost from its very inception, Protestantism split
  into a variety of competing belief systems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089388Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-empire-conquest
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Empire was always about conquest."@en ;
  curric:correction """In fact, empire was often an ad-hoc private affair. For example, the East
  India Company had taken control over large parts of India - an expansion driven by
  opportunistic officials largely acting independently of the British government."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089628Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mughal-authority-collapsed-17th-century
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mughal authority collapsed in the 17th century."@en ;
  curric:correction """Mughal rule faced challenges, but the emperors still had enough military
  power and political control to maintain their authority during the 17th century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-napoleon-became-emperor-france-seized
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Napoleon became Emperor of France after he seized power from the Directory in
  1799."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Napoleon became First Consul after seizing power from the Directory, but did
  not crown himself Emperor of France until 1804."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089828Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-kings-power-whatever-want-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Kings have the power to do whatever they want in their own countries."@en ;
  curric:correction """For a great deal of English history, the power of the kings has been
  restricted by English laws and religious laws issued by the pope in Rome."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-catholic-priests-allowed-get-married
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Catholic priests have never been allowed to get married."@en ;
  curric:correction """Catholic priests today are not allowed to get married, but in the past a
  great many were, even though it went against their rules. Some popes even had wives and
  children!"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089950Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-victorian-women-played-political-role
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Victorian women played no political role in Britain in the 19th century."@en ;
  curric:correction """Women were increasingly politically active in Britain, for example, through
  their involvement in the abolitionist movement and through their participation in trade
  unions, despite being unable to vote."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090048Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-scottish-people-time-followed-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Scottish people at the time followed the same type of Protestantism."@en ;
  curric:correction """Scotland at this time was experiencing a serious split in the Protestant
  religion between Episcopalians and Presbyterians. The Episcopalians supported James while
  the Presbyterians supported William III."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-towns-cities-called-same-name
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Towns and cities are called by the same name as they were given when they were
  founded."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Towns and cities all over the world have changed their name repeatedly for a
  wide variety of reasons. For example, York was called Eboracum by the Romans, Eoforwick by
  the Saxons and Jorvik by the Vikings!"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090179Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-historians-study-same-things-history
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Historians all study the same things in history."@en ;
  curric:correction """There is a large and ever-growing variety of themes that historians look at
  in history that shape the way we view the past, e.g. military history, economic history,
  women's history and many more."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090221Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-french-cartoons-complimentary-napoleon-british
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All French cartoons are complimentary of Napoleon and all British cartoons are
  critical of Napoleon."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many French cartoons were critical of Napoleon and many British cartoons were
  critical of the British government's response to his actions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090405Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-laws-regularly-scrutinised-updated-government
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Laws are regularly scrutinised and updated by the government."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many laws remain unchanged and in place for an exceedingly long time.
  Sometimes new laws are created which make the old ones redundant, but other times there is
  no need to replace the existing law if it is still relevant."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090456Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-women-medieval-norwich-same-experience
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All women in medieval Norwich had the same experience as one another."@en ;
  curric:correction """Female experiences were varied, especially by wealth and social class. Those
  from wealthier backgrounds were more likely to be literate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090529Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-parliament-fought-civil-wars-remove
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Parliament fought both Civil Wars to remove Charles I from power"@en ;
  curric:correction """The majority of people in Parliament wanted to change how Charles I behaved
  but only a minority wanted to remove the king from power."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090537Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-because-printing-presses
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think that because printing presses were mechanical, they were as
  fast and efficient as modern machinery."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that even though printing presses were much quicker than
  copying by hand, it could still take a relatively long time to print books."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090674Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-england-comparable-colonial
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils think that England was a comparable colonial power to Spain in the 16th
  century."""@en ;
  curric:correction """English colonisation attempts began much later than Spain’s, and occurred on
  a much smaller-scale with less government involvement."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091012Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-surnames-used-generally-arent-changed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Surnames have always been used and they generally aren't changed from one
  generation to the next."""@en ;
  curric:correction """During the medieval period, people went by their first name and one or more
  given names. These given names could be nicknames based on their place of origin or
  occupation or a distinguishing feature. Some people chose their own given names."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091023Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-akbars-religious-tolerance-absolute-throughout
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Akbar's religious tolerance was absolute throughout his reign."@en ;
  curric:correction """Akbar made some exceptions to his general policy of religious tolerance, such
  as when he declared a jihad against the Hindu Kingdom of Mewar."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091076Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-east-india-company-relied-entirely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The East India Company relied entirely on European soldiers."@en ;
  curric:correction """The EIC increasingly recruited sepoy soldiers to serve in its army from the
  late-1740s onwards."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091103Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-large-variety-names-people-called
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There has always been a large variety of names that people could be
  called."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In societies that do not experience a great deal of immigration, the pool of
  names that people can be called can be limited. This was the case for hundreds of years in
  England, causing many people to share the same names (e.g. Thomas!)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-history-relevant-today
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "History is not relevant to today."@en ;
  curric:correction """Henry II’s reforms to the English legal system established the foundation of
  English common law, still in use today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091471Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-elizabeth-first-female-ruler-england
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Elizabeth was the first female ruler of England."@en ;
  curric:correction """There were female rulers before Elizabeth, including her sister Mary I
  immediately preceeding her."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091482Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-napoleon-exiled-once
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Napoleon was only exiled once."@en ;
  curric:correction """Napoleon was exiled twice. The first time to Elba after his defeat in Russia.
  He escaped back to France and gained support from his old troops and took power once more.
  He was defeated at Waterloo and exiled for the final time to St Helena."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092194Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-majority-women-worked-factories-throughout
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The majority of women worked in factories throughout this period."@en ;
  curric:correction """The work women did and whether they worked at all was largely determined by
  class. From the mid-19th century, legislation placed restrictions on the type and amount
  of work women were able to do and the number of women working in factories decreased."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092303Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-assume-political-instability-result
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students assume political instability is only the result of foreign powers
  challenging the leaders of a country."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Political instability at the start of Humayun's reign partly occurred because
  of rebellions by his younger brothers and political instability in the 1550s was created
  by descendants of Sher Shah fighting one another for power."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092308Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-eyewitness-accounts-produce
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that 'eyewitness' accounts produce a more reliable picture
  of historical events."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although 'eyewitness' accounts are valuable, they were produced for a
  particular purpose which may distort their contents."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092381Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-records-speeches-previous-time-periods
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Records of speeches from previous time periods are accurate representations of
  what these people actually said."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Accurate recording of speeches was not a priority for many historians or
  record keepers up until fairly recently. It was seen as acceptable to put words into the
  mouths of past people based on what happened after or to reflect present sensibilities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093519Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-1701-act-settlement-meant-parliament
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The 1701 Act of Settlement meant that parliament no longer needed to worry
  about a Catholic taking the throne in the future."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although the 1701 Act of Settlement stipulated a Catholic or the spouse of a
  Catholic could never succeed to the throne of England, parliament remained worried that a
  succession crisis could still ensue if a monarch died childless."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093565Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-european-settlement-completely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils assume that European settlement completely destroyed indigenous
  communities."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Native Americans were devastated overall by European colonisation but
  indigenous communities persisted and were never completely overwhelmed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094883Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-parliament-ruled-country-whole-interregnum
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Parliament ruled the country for the whole Interregnum period."@en ;
  curric:correction """Parliament ruled the country at the start of the Interregnum but was
  dismissed, recomposed, and ruled without at other times after 1652."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.096354Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-single-person-cannot-shape-history
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A single person cannot shape history by themselves."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Great Man Theory in History - the idea that a single person is
  responsible for important events - is somewhat outdated, but occasionally, as is the case
  with Martin Luther, an argument can be made that individuals can radically shape events."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097697Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-black-death-terrible-one-event
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Black Death was a terrible one-off event."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although the Black Death was a one-off event, the plague, the disease that
  was the Black Death, continued to afflict Europe for hundreds of years after it first came
  to Europe in the 14th century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099096Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-governments-societies-generally-sympathetic-people
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Governments and societies have generally been sympathetic to people in extreme
  poverty who may have been reduced to begging."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Throughout much of history, there has been little sympathy for people in
  extreme poverty from the majority of governments and societies, even when the
  circumstances that drove people into poverty are clearly out of their own control."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-african-kingdoms-rulers-willingly-participated
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All African kingdoms and rulers willingly participated in the Transatlantic
  Slave Trade."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Some kingdoms did cooperate, but many - like the Kingdom of Benin - also
  tried to resist by refusing to trade enslaved people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103711Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-primary-sources-inherently-useful-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Primary sources are inherently useful because they were published at the time
  of an event."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Sources are produced for a variety of purposes which can affect what they
  say. Propaganda sources might falsify information to persuade."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-successor-states-completely-ignored-mughal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The successor states completely ignored the Mughal Emperor's authority."@en ;
  curric:correction """Successor states took a lot of power for themselves but still claimed to be
  loyal to the Mughals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107344Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-britain-involved-transatlantic-slave-trade
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Britain was always involved in the Transatlantic Slave Trade."@en ;
  curric:correction """Britain became involved in the trade in the 1500s, initially selling enslaved
  people onto plantations in Spanish and Portuguese colonies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108056Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-illegal-children-get-married
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It has always been illegal for children to get married."@en ;
  curric:correction """Throughout history, royal children were regularly betrothed at a young age in
  order to secure alliances between nations. Marriage followed later when the children had
  grown up, although they regularly still married younger than we do today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108236Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-past-changes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The past never changes."@en ;
  curric:correction """Our understanding of the past changes frequently, which causes us to look at
  events in different ways. As such, how we view the past is constantly changing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108516Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-farmers-starve-because-grow-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Farmers will not starve because they grow their own food."@en ;
  curric:correction """Poor harvests can put a great deal of strain on the amount of food a farmer
  can grow, even food for subsistence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109266Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-expansion-empire-means-growing-stronger
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Expansion of an empire always means that is growing stronger."@en ;
  curric:correction """As the Mughal Empire expanded, the costs of maintaining its rule across India
  also increased and new tensions were created with groups who lost out from extended Mughal
  control."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109562Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-medieval-modern-church-power-equivalent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Medieval and modern Church power is equivalent."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explicitly outline the Church's organisational power: land ownership, clergy
  social status, and spiritual authority."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109567Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-historical-events-one-cause
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Historical events have one cause."@en ;
  curric:correction """This will be addressed across the course of the unit, but within this lesson
  it is worth drawing attention to the competing causes listed in the discussion of the
  Peasants' Revolt."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-belief-margaret-anjou-vicious-unpleasant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The belief that Margaret of Anjou was a vicious and unpleasant woman."@en ;
  curric:correction """A woman who held power would have likely been criticised in the medieval
  period and Yorkists would also have wanted to show her in an unfavourable light."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110390Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-violence-important-reign-monarchs-such
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Violence was not important during the reign of some monarchs such as Akbar the
  Great."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Violence was consistently part of the reigns of Mughal emperors. Akbar
  ordered the massacre of 30 000 people living in Mewar after they resisted the Mughal army
  in 1568."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110410Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-become-confused-number-historical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may become confused by the number of historical figures that share
  the same name."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Ensure students can differentiate between Edward IV and Prince Edward."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110915Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-christians-saved-holy-land-barbaric
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Christians 'saved' the Holy Land from barbaric Muslim conquerors."@en ;
  curric:correction """Muslims had generally treated Christians very well during the 400 or so years
  that they had controlled the Holy Land. In contrast, when the Christian crusaders arrived
  in the Holy Land they engaged in barbaric acts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111068Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-medieval-islamic-world-single-entity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The medieval Islamic world was a single entity."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Islamic Empire started as a single entity, but by the 11th century had
  fragmented into several competing nations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111410Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-power-associated-land
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that power associated with land ownership was a Norman import
  to England."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that Anglo-Saxon England was a society largely based on land
  ownership and the power that this brought."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111915Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-written-word-useful-source-study
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The written word is the only useful source for the study of the past."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although written sources are useful, material remains can reveal much about
  past societies - it depends on the questions historians ask of the source."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111924Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-king-dies-taken-prisoner
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Once a king dies or is taken prisoner, that is the end of the war."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although a king is very important, there are many examples throughout history
  of a king's followers continuing to fight on successfully after their leader has been
  killed or captured."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112101Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-women-england-allowed-fight-wars
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Women in England were not allowed to fight in wars."@en ;
  curric:correction """We have many examples of women leading the defence of castles throughout
  English history, and occasionally leading the attack on enemy territory as well. It was
  uncommon, but not unheard of."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112747Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-impossible-large-numbers-people-cross
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It is impossible for large numbers of people to cross the Sahara Desert."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although extremely dangerous, the Sahara Desert has been crossed many times
  by large groups of people. Large amounts of provisions are needed though, which is why it
  is not a common occurrance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115382Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-consider-sources-inherently-useful
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may consider sources to be inherently useful or not useful and make
  statements about bias."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that all sources are useful for investigating something, and
  that the questions we ask of them are important in this process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117540Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-successful-empires-dominate-subjugate-conquered
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Successful empires dominate and subjugate the conquered people within the
  empire in order to keep them loyal."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Mali aristocracy adopted a successful 'hands off' approach to governance,
  allowing the different kingdoms within the empire a great degree of autonomy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.118405Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-realise-women-well-men
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might not realise that women as well as men were conscripted during
  WW2."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In 1940, single women aged 20-30, and widowed women without children, were
  conscripted into war work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.118727Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-prior-mughal-conquest-india-ruled
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Prior to the Mughal conquest, India was all ruled by a single state."@en ;
  curric:correction """Multiple states ruled over India prior to Babur's successful invasion from
  1525-27. In northern India this included a mix of Muslim and Hindu-led states."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.118830Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-women-forbidden-ruling-their-own
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Women were forbidden from ruling in their own right in England during the
  medieval period."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The first time the concept of a woman ruling in her own right in England
  occurred it took everyone by surprise. No one had considered that a woman might rule
  alone, so there was no law preventing it from happening."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119847Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-bolsheviks-revolutionary-background-meant-completely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Bolsheviks revolutionary background meant that they were completely
  different to the tsar."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Bolsheviks treated opposition similarly to the tsar, using a secret
  police and re-introducing censorship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.120775Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-learn-little-imagery
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that we can learn little from imagery that has been produced
  for the purposes of propaganda."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that we can learn a lot from such imagery as it is a window
  into the minds of those who had it produced, and helps us to understand some of their
  concerns and motivations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.120784Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-empires-own-land-order-control
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Empires have to own land in order to control it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Control can be gained through a variety of indirect means, such as through
  trade or tribute."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.122683Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ghana-empire-located-modern-day
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Ghana Empire was located in the modern-day country of Ghana."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Ghana Empire was located in the Sahel, north of the Niger River, which is
  nowhere near the modern-day country of Ghana."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.122712Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-sources-greater-inherent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may believe that some sources have a greater inherent value than
  others."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that a source's value rests entirely upon the enquiry for which
  it is used and the questions asked of it. No source has inherent value unless used as part
  of an enquiry."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.125314Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-existence-female-rulers-like-elizabeth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The existence of female rulers like Elizabeth I and Mary, Queen of Scots,
  meant that women in early modern Britain had significantly more power than in the medieval
  period."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It was extremely rare for women to wield power during this period. Early
  modern Britain was a patriarchal society in which society was controlled by men and the
  vast majority of women were excluded from all positions of power and influence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.125514Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-many-ideas-renaissance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that many of the ideas of the Renaissance were new to
  science, literature and art."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that the Renaissance was a period during which knowledge
  lost in Western Europe was rediscovered, rather than created for the first time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.129548Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-followers-same-religion-practise-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All followers of the same religion practise their religion in the same
  way."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are often large differences between followers of the same religion:
  people include elements of their own culture in their worship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131085Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-black-death-affected-europe
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Black Death only affected Europe."@en ;
  curric:correction """European records from the time are numerous and detailed, so we have a very
  clear idea about the impact of the Black Death on Europe. However, the Black Death
  affected a large geographic area, including places without detailed records of the impact."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.136359Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-muslims-mainly-live-middle-east
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Muslims mainly live in the Middle East."@en ;
  curric:correction """Islam is the second most popular religion in the world, with Muslim-majority
  countries spread as far as Morocco in the west to Indonesia in the east."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.142713Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-different-religious-denominations-believe-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Different religious denominations believe very different things from each
  other."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Different denominations within a religion will almost certainly believe the
  same fundamental things about their religion, but will differ over the details of belief
  or liturgy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.146797Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-involving-parliament-rule-land-meant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Involving Parliament with the rule of the land meant there would be more
  fairness and justice."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Parliament passed discriminatory laws: handing more power to parliament did
  not necessarily mean a growth in rights and freedoms for all."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.147193Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-reason-why-crusaders-went-first
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The only reason why crusaders went on the First Crusade was to capture
  Jerusalem for Christianity."""@en ;
  curric:correction """People went on crusade for a wide variety of reasons; for some people,
  capturing Jerusalem from the Muslims was important, but it was almost certainly not the
  reason why the First Crusade was called in the first place."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.148164Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believed-yorkists-lancastrians-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may believed that the Yorkists and Lancastrians were from different
  families."""@en ;
  curric:correction "The Lancastrians and Yorkists were both part of the Plantagenet family."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.149695Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-christianity-single-religion
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Christianity is a single religion."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are more than 45 000 different Christian denominations around the world
  today: although most of them believe the same fundamental things, there are stark
  differences between many of them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.149834Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-industrial-revolution-led-decline-living
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Industrial Revolution led to a decline in living conditions across all
  parts of Britain."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The decline in living conditions during the Industrial Revolution was
  generally confined to industrial towns and their poorest areas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150427Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-main-aim-rebels-peasants-revolt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the main aim of the rebels in the Peasants' Revolt was to overthrow the
  king."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In fact the rebels' grievances were against local officials and the king's
  advisers, who they believed were misleading the king into acting against the interests of
  his people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150437Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-british-troops-began-fighting-against
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """British troops began fighting against Nazi Germany immediately after war was
  declared."""@en ;
  curric:correction """For eight months, there was very limited British, French and German military
  land operation on the Western Front. This became known as the 'Phoney War'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150444Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hitler-unpopular-dictator
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Hitler was always an unpopular dictator."@en ;
  curric:correction """Hitler often attracted enthusiastic crowds to his speeches. By January 1933,
  the popularity of Hitler and the Nazi Party had turned into an electoral success."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.154828Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-akbar-remembered-strong-military-leader
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Akbar is remembered as a strong military leader because he only used violence
  to expand the Mughal Empire."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Akbar used a variety of methods to expand the Mughal Empire. In some cases,
  such as to gain control over the Rajput states, diplomacy was more important for expansion
  under Akbar than violence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155181Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-challenged-portuguese-began-buying
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """No one challenged the Portuguese when they began buying enslaved people to
  take to the Americas."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many rulers and local people in West Africa were opposed to the trading of
  enslaved people from the very beginning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155991Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-atomic-bombs-dropped-japan-immediate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The atomic bombs dropped on Japan only had immediate impacts."@en ;
  curric:correction """The bombs had unprecedented destructive power. They sent out a shock wave
  that incinerated everything within a four-mile radius and in the weeks that followed,
  people died from radiation poisoning despite having survived the initial blast."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.157309Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-resistance-involves-use-violence
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Resistance always involves the use of violence."@en ;
  curric:correction """Jews adopted many nonviolent forms of resistance. Actions like smuggling
  resisted Nazi attempts to starve Jews and continuing education secretly resisted Nazi
  attempts to destroy Jewish culture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.157714Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-peoples-revolted-saint-domingue-enslaved
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All the peoples who revolted in Saint-Domingue were enslaved people."@en ;
  curric:correction """The revolutionaries of Saint-Domingue were comprised of a combination of
  enslaved people, free people of African descent and free indigenous people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.158679Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-muslim-island-little-diversity-11th
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "As a Muslim island, there was little diversity in 11th century Sicily."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sicily was amongst the most diverse places in Eurasia during the 11th century
  with a population of Muslims, Christians and Jews."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.159052Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-caribbean-countries-gained-independence-britain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Caribbean countries gained independence from Britain at the same time."@en ;
  curric:correction """Jamaica and Trinidad and Tobago were the first of Britain's Caribbean
  colonies to achieve independence in 1962, however, the last British colony in the
  Caribbean to gain independence was Saint Kitts and Nevis in 1983."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.159058Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sait-domingue-independent-france-toussaint
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Sait-Domingue was independent from France under Toussaint L'Ouverture's
  leadership"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Toussaint L'Ouverture was technically the French Governor of Saint-Domingue
  due to his leadership during the slave uprising there during the 1790s. His attempt to
  establish the colony as a free country though in 1801 was a step too far for Napoleon."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.159068Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-view-work-women-support-war
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The view that it was the work women did to support the war effort which gained
  them the right to vote."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many people were convinced women should be entitled to vote before 1914;
  however, the violence of the suffragettes and the interruption of WW1 delayed this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.159076Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-assume-english-army-comprised
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may assume that the English army only comprised English soldiers."@en ;
  curric:correction """The English forces also included Welsh and even some Scottish soldiers. This
  reflects the complex political and military alliances of the time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.159238Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-french-revolution-occurred-because-enlightenment
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The French Revolution only occurred because of the Enlightenment."@en ;
  curric:correction """The French Revolution occurred for a myriad of reasons. These include causes
  such as the Enlightenment, the influence of the American Revolution, the lavish spending
  of the monarchy and their supposed indifference to the plight of the Third Estate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.159243Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enlightenment-philosophers-atheists-rejected-religion
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All Enlightenment philosophers were atheists and rejected religion
  entirely."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Enlightenment philosophers wanted to reshape and redefine the role religion
  and the Church played in society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.159252Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-kings-adults-ultimate-decision-makers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All kings are adults and are the ultimate decision makers."@en ;
  curric:correction """Henry III became king when he was nine-years-old. As he was too young,
  regents were appointed to rule on Henry’s behalf."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.159423Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-welsh-resistance-unified-movement
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Welsh resistance was always a unified movement."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many Welsh princes cooperated with Edward's Welsh campaign in 1277. Edward’s
  army also included 9000 Welsh soldiers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.159555Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-campaigners-reform-like-bpu-wanted
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Most campaigners for reform like the BPU wanted all adults in Britain to be
  enfranchised."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The BPU campaigned for tax-paying males to be enfranchised, which would have
  continued to exclude many poor workers as well as women."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poor-accepted-their-position-medieval
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The poor always accepted their position in medieval society."@en ;
  curric:correction """The poor challenged the social order in Norwich violently in 1381 and had to
  be actively managed by the elites."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160250Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-european-merchants-arrived-west-africa
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """European merchants arrived in West Africa with the intention of starting to
  enslave people."""@en ;
  curric:correction """European merchants were attracted by the potential amount of gold they would
  be able to trade in West Africa."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160260Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-france-existed-unified-nation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That France existed as a unified nation."@en ;
  curric:correction """\"Modern-day France\" did not exist yet, instead the area we know as France,
  was actually a collection of separate lands/duchies ."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160370Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-element-nhs-free-considerable-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Every element of the NHS was free for a considerable time after its
  creation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Every element of the NHS was only free for a short time, as the overwhelming
  demand resulted in the need to introduce prescription fees."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160376Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-declaration-independence-signed-settlers-defeated
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Declaration of Independence was signed after the settlers defeated the
  British in the Revolutionary War."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Declaration of Independence was signed early on in the Revolutionary War
  and the US Constitution was signed after the war had concluded."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160464Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-leaders-lodz-ghetto-made-bad
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Leaders in the Lodz Ghetto made 'bad' choices for choosing to comply with
  German orders."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Leaders in the Lodz Ghetto, like many other Jews, faced multiple poor choices
  - or 'choiceless choices'. The decisions they made occurred in extreme circumstances where
  they had little real control over their own survival."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160470Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-suffragists-same-suffragettes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Suffragists were the same as suffragettes."@en ;
  curric:correction """One way for pupils to remember the difference is that the suffraGETtes wanted
  to GET things done - deeds not words."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160476Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-edward-intended-conquer-scotland-add
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Edward I always intended to conquer Scotland and add it to his kingdom."@en ;
  curric:correction """Edward I's initial aim was to have the Scottish pay him homage as their
  overlord."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160753Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-haitian-rebels-enslaved-people
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All the Haitian rebels were enslaved people."@en ;
  curric:correction "Many of the Haitian rebels were free people."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-parliament-powerful-organisation-rules-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Parliament is a powerful organisation that rules the country."@en ;
  curric:correction "At this point in history, the role of parliament was to advise the king."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160892Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-belief-edward-military-strength-alone
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There is a belief that Edward I's military strength alone was sufficient to
  ensure long-term control and unity of Britain."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Edward I's approach was often brutal leading to ongoing resistance and
  ultimately limiting his ability to achieve lasting unification."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160999Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-magna-carta-singular-event-resulted
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Magna Carta was a singular event which resulted in a powerless monarchy and
  human rights for all."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Magna Carta started a process of struggle. The medieval monarchy remained
  powerful, and it did not grant freedoms to everybody."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161005Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-aassume-william-beveridge-member
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may aassume William Beveridge was a member of the Labour Party."@en ;
  curric:correction "William Beveridge was actually a member of the Liberal Party."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161135Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ideas-racial-superiority-justification-british
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Ideas of racial superiority were the only justification for British
  imperialism."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Cultural and religious beliefs such as a belief in the superiority of
  Christianity helped to justify an encourage British imperialism throughout the 19th
  century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161239Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-belief-women-supported-war-women
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The belief that all women supported the war, and that women were immediately
  involved in war work from 1914."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Some women were pacifists and did not support the war effort. Women were only
  brought into the workforce from 1916 due to labour shortages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161266Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-irish-nationalists-shared-same-views
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Irish nationalists shared the same views and had the same aims."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some Irish nationalists wanted Home Rule for Ireland whereas other
  nationalists (known as republicans) wanted complete independence from Britain. After 1921,
  republicans split between those who supported the Anglo-Irish Treaty and those who did
  not."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161501Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nazi-antisemitism-meant-immediately-violent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Nazi antisemitism meant they were immediately violent towards Jews."@en ;
  curric:correction "Open violence as a part of Nazi persecution only became common in 1938."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161506Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-britain-england-terms-describe-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Britain and England are terms which describe the same area."@en ;
  curric:correction "Britain is the name for England, Scotland, and Wales."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-industrial-revolution-affected-aspects-life
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Industrial Revolution affected all aspects of life in Britain equally."@en ;
  curric:correction """The impact of the Industrial Revolution may be measured differently depending
  on which aspects of life historians focus their attention on."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161670Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-king-john-ruled-england
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "King John only ruled England."@en ;
  curric:correction """King John inherited the Angevin Empire which stretched across England and
  France."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161886Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-native-american-same-part-single
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Native American were the same and part of a single society."@en ;
  curric:correction """There was a wide range of indigenous nations in the Americas, with many
  differences between their sizes, social structure and cultures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162146Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-historians-agree-happened-past
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Historians all agree about what happened in the past."@en ;
  curric:correction """Historians are constantly arguing and changing their minds about events in
  the past as new evidence comes to light."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-rationing-ended-second
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might believe rationing ended when the Second World War ended in
  1945."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Rationing continued in Britain until 1954."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162253Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-john-rolfes-marriage-pocahontas-represented
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """John Rolfe’s marriage to Pocahontas represented goodwill between colonists and
  the Powhatan tribe."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Pocahontas' marriage involved her capture and forced conversion to
  Christianity. Pocahontas was used by the English for their own advantage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162341Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-presume-everyone-descendants-windrush
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might presume that everyone the descendants of the Windrush
  generation had the automatic right to stay and work in Britain."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The children of Windrush generation did not have their own passports, and it
  was difficult to prove they had entered the UK legally. This led to the Windrush Scandal
  in 2018."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162347Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-german-nazis-involved-holocaust
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only German Nazis were involved in the Holocaust."@en ;
  curric:correction """Examples such as the Vel' d'Hiv Raid in France, carried out in 1942, show
  that other Europeans collaborated and helped to perpetrate the Holocaust."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162352Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-because-renaissance-architects
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think that because Renaissance architects used mathematical
  calculations to design their buildings, these were without subsequent problems or issues."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that these architects often made miscalculations and many
  subsequent improvement works were needed to ensure buildings like St Peter's did not fall
  down."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162389Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-abolition-slavery-britain-its-colonies
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Abolition of slavery in Britain and its colonies was a response to a single
  event."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Abolition of slavery in Britain and its colonies was a response to a number
  of events and an ever-growing public demand for change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-toussaint-louverture-fighting-against-french
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Toussaint L'Ouverture was fighting against the French during the entirety of
  the Haitian Revolution."""@en ;
  curric:correction """He first fought Saint-Domingue's ruling French elites and slave-owners. He
  then fought Spanish troops after invading Spain's territory on the island. He then
  defeated a British invasion and became Haiti's official governor until France betrayed
  him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162515Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-revolutions-involve-execution-previous-leaders
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Revolutions always involve the execution of the previous leaders of
  government."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although there was violence during the February Revolution, Tsar Nicholas II
  agreed to abdicate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162520Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-historically-contribution-colonial-troops-war
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Historically the contribution of colonial troops to the war effort has been
  overlooked."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Colonial troops made significant contributions to the war, both within Europe
  and across the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162528Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-medieval-queens-little-influence
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Medieval queens had little influence."@en ;
  curric:correction """Eleanor was an intelligent and powerful queen, acted as regent, and was a key
  conspirator of the revolt."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162649Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-haitian-revolution-directly-inspired-abolition
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Haitian Revolution directly inspired the abolition of slavery
  everywhere."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The events of the Haitian Revolution strengthened Britain's abolitionist
  movement and helped France to initially abolish slavery in 1794; but under Napoleon the
  threat of enslavement returned."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162657Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-role-medieval-monarch
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that the role of the medieval monarch is comparable with
  today's monarchy."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A medieval king was judged by his ability on the battlefield. Success in
  battle was the best way for a king to become powerful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-medieval-women-completed-work-other
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Medieval women completed no work other than housework and looking after
  children."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although they were responsible for housework and childcare and did not have
  the same opportunities to work as men, women in the medieval period completed a range of
  other work; the type of work they completed was determined by where they lived."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162716Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-bayeux-tapestry-biased-source-therefore
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the Bayeux Tapestry is a 'biased' source and therefore not useful to
  historians."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although all sources were produced in a particular context, historians can
  ask careful questions of them to learn about the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162722Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-borders-drawn-partition-clear-accepted
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The borders drawn during Partition were clear and accepted by all."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Radcliffe Line, which demarcated the borders, was highly contentious and
  led to significant disputes and confusion, which resulted in violence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162962Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sole-turning-point-second-world
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the sole turning point of the Second World War was due to America being
  brought into the conflict."""@en ;
  curric:correction """America's entry into the conflict was an important turning point, however,
  another significant turning point occurred with the first defeat of the Nazi army in the
  Soviet Union."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163081Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-decolonisation-happened-peaceful-orderly-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Decolonisation happened in a peaceful and orderly way in all of Britain's
  African colonies."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Decolonisation in many of Britain's African colonies was mostly peaceful;
  however, there were exceptions. For example, in Kenya there was significant violence as
  the British authorities used brutal measures to suppress the Mau Mau Uprising (1952-60)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163163Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-britain-historic-role-creation-tension
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That Britain has no historic role in the creation of tension between Arabs and
  Jews over Palestine."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Britain's colonial role in Palestine during and after the First World War
  involved it making conflicting promises to both Arabs and Jews over Palestine's future."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163259Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shared-jewish-heritage-meant-european
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Shared Jewish heritage meant that all European Jews lived similar lives."@en ;
  curric:correction """Jews made individuals choices and were affected by factors such as wealth
  which led to the Jewish population living many different types of lives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163264Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-suffrage-movement-involved-violent-illegal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The suffrage movement always involved violent or illegal tactics as well as
  peaceful and legal ones."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The early suffragist movement was committed to peaceful tactics, even among
  the so-called 'radical suffragists'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163340Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-impact-wwi-limited-europe-directly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The impact of WWI was limited to Europe, and those directly affected by the
  deaths of troops."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The impact of WWI can be seen in Britain across different groups in society,
  but also within British colonies across the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163348Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-king-john-signed-magna-carta
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "King John signed the Magna Carta."@en ;
  curric:correction """A modern misconception is that King John signed Magna Carta, this is untrue,
  royal documents were not signed but sealed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163398Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-1807-slave-trade-act-freed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The 1807 Slave Trade Act freed all enslaved people in the British Empire."@en ;
  curric:correction """The 1807 Slave Trade Act did not free all enslaved people in the British
  Empire, but did ban the buying, selling and transportation of enslaved individuals from
  that point forward."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163446Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-knew-agreed-countries-made
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Everyone knew what was agreed by countries which had made alliances before the
  start of the war."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that important parts of the alliance agreements were not made public
  so other countries did not know about them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-jews-murdered-holocaust-killed-gas
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Most Jews murdered during the Holocaust were killed in gas chambers in
  concentration camps."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Gas chambers were set up in specially constructed extermination camps for
  Jews and killed millions, but roughly half of all Holocaust victims were killed by other
  means."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163726Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-medieval-islamic-states
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils assume that all medieval Islamic states must have been identical to one
  another."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Islamic states had similarities and differences (i.e. Cordoba had many
  Mediterranean influences; Persian influence was stronger in Baghdad)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163732Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-assassination-ferdinand-led-inevitable-immediate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the assassination of Ferdinand led to the inevitable, immediate outbreak
  of a global war"""@en ;
  curric:correction """The outbreak of the war was the result of a series of context-dependent
  events, including the Austrian ultimatum and the Schlieffen Plan"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163861Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-radicals-encouraged-use-violence-solve
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Radicals encouraged the use of violence to solve the problems that industrial
  workers faced."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Radicals like Cobbett and Hunt emphaisised the importance of peaceful
  protests and the need to persuade government to extend voting rights."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-holocaust-confined-germany
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Holocaust was confined to Germany."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Nazis and their collaborators murdered 6 million Jews from across Europe
  and aimed to eliminate Jews from the entire continent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163968Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-british-empire-different-other-european
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The British Empire was different from other European empires because Britain
  willingly relinquished control of its colonies and decolonisation was mostly a peaceful
  process."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While it was a peaceful process in some British colonies, decolonisation
  involved significant violence in other colonies. Even in colonies where decolonisation was
  relatively peaceful there was some violence (e.g., Accra Riots in the Gold Coast)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163988Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-transatlantic-slave-trade-made-large
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Transatlantic Slave Trade made up a large percentage of Britain’s national
  income."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The direct profit from the trade in enslaved people was 1% of Britain’s
  national income. However, much more wealth was generated in Britain from the trade in
  products produced by enslaved labour, and by provisioning the Transatlantic Slave Trade."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163996Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enlightenment-thinkers-racist
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Enlightenment thinkers were racist."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some Enlightenment thinkers promoted racist theories while others advocated
  for equality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164071Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-britain-europe-engaged-empire-building
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only Britain and Europe engaged in empire building."@en ;
  curric:correction """In fact, empires have existed across the world since at least the ancient
  period: several dynasties ruled across China, the Ottoman Empire spanned across Asia,
  Africa and Europe, and the Mali Empire controlled extensive territories in West Africa."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164128Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-trend-british-imperial-decline-caused
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The trend of British imperial decline was caused by foreign policy and
  external threats."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There is a link between foreign and domestic policy, both of which
  contributed to imperial decline."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-britain-ruled-large-areas-africa
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Britain ruled over large areas of Africa throughout the 19th century."@en ;
  curric:correction """British colonies were mainly confined to coastal areas in the first half of
  the 19th century. It was only later that British rule extended into the African interior."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164194Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nobility-england-identified-english
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The nobility in England identified as English."@en ;
  curric:correction """This period marks a time when the nobility, who had their ancestral roots in
  France, had now come to see themselves as English."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164203Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-industrial-revolution-use-steam-power
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the Industrial Revolution was only about the use of steam power."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many key changes in the Industrial Revolution related to developments beyond
  the use of steam power, such as the exploitation of water power."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-womens-suffrage-led-rapid-increase
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Women's suffrage led to a rapid increase in the number of female MPs in
  Parliament."""@en ;
  curric:correction """By 1931, there were only 15 female MPs in Parliament; however, women's
  suffrage meant that MPs were more likely to support new laws that had a positive impact on
  the lives of women."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164329Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-get-confused-edward-prince
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may get confused between Edward, Prince of Wales and Edward IV."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that Edward, Prince of Wales, is the only son of Henry VI and
  Margaret of Anjou, and a Lancastrian. Edward IV is the son of Richard, Duke of York, who
  became Edward IV, and a Yorkist."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164335Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-murder-thomas-becket-undoing-henry
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The murder of Thomas Becket was the undoing of Henry II."@en ;
  curric:correction """Long-term it increased Henry’s control over the Church. Bishops’ opposition
  decreased, while the Pope gave support after 1172."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164540Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-people-control-nationalised
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils might think that the people had control of nationalised industries."@en ;
  curric:correction """The first chairman of the National Coal Board (NCB) was the former owner of
  the largest coal company in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164546Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-died-russian-civil-war
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """People only died in the Russian Civil War as a direct result of the
  fighting."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Millions of ordinary Russians died as a result of methods like the Red Terror
  and War Communism used by the Reds during the war."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164993Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-medieval-period-completed-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That all people in the medieval period completed the same type of work as one
  another."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind students that a wide range of different jobs and industries existed in
  medieval Norwich, even after it focused more on wools."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165121Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-statute-labourers-immediately-forced-peasants
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the Statute of Labourers immediately forced all peasants to return to
  their home manors and to cease negotiating higher wages."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Through the interpretations section of the lesson, draw out the point that
  the Statute of Labourers was unenforceable in many cases."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165127Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rise-germany-usa-growth-nationalist
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The rise of Germany and the USA and the growth of nationalist movements in the
  late 19th century contributed to imperial decline."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The British Empire responded to this rise in anxiety by showcasing their
  supremacy at Queen Victoria's Diamond Jubilee."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165380Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-assume-communists-socialists-shared
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students assume all communists and socialists shared the same ideas."@en ;
  curric:correction """Marx's ideas were interpreted differently by different groups of socialists.
  In Russia, this led to the split of the Social Democratic Party."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165557Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-assume-revolutions-lead-complete
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students assume that revolutions lead to complete change."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that there were significant changes in Russia after 1917 but
  similarities remained, such as the lack of freedom for opposition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165563Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-increased-powers-self-government-norwich
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Increased powers of self government in Norwich gave all locals more control
  over decision-making."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Only freemen had real political power in Norwich but very few women and
  almost no poor people were able to become freemen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165613Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-medieval-churches-focused
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that medieval churches only focused on prayer and religious
  services."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that the Cathedral and other groups of churchmen in medieval
  Norwich also provided charity, education and hospital care."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165652Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-revolts-rebellions-driven-purely-rage
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Revolts and rebellions are driven purely by rage and frustration."@en ;
  curric:correction """Most revolts and rebellions have a number of causes and are usually led by
  people with a plan and aims to achieve."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.166005Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-king-rule-without
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might believe that the king could rule without the support ot the
  nobility."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that the king relied on nobles to keep law and order in society,
  particularly in more remote parts of the kingdom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.166112Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-walpole-created-role-prime-minister
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Walpole created the role of Prime Minister and the idea of Cabinet."@en ;
  curric:correction """Walpole's leadership saw him become de-facto Prime Minister and he formalised
  the idea of Cabinet which already existed in a loose, unofficial form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.166225Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-america-britain-won-war-defeating
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "America and Britain won the war by defeating the Nazis in Berlin."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Soviets had pushed the Nazi army back across eastern Europe; four out of
  five German soldiers killed in WW2 were killed on the Eastern Front."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.166633Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-britain-first-country-give-women
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Britain was the first country to give women the right to vote."@en ;
  curric:correction """New Zealand was the first country in which women gained the right to vote, in
  1893. Australia was the next, nine years later."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.166638Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-because-abbasid-caliphate-large-caliphs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Because the Abbasid Caliphate was large, the caliphs must have retained a lot
  of power."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that the caliphs had little effective power beyond Baghdad
  itself by the 11th century and the Seljuks became de facto rulers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.166852Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-working-class-men-gained-right
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All working class men gained the right to vote due to the 1867 and 1884 Reform
  Acts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """As property qualifications remained in place, a significant proportion of
  working class adult men remained unable to vote even after 1884."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.168501Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-same-social-group-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All people from the same social group had the same experiences."@en ;
  curric:correction """Experiences could vary even between people from the same social group,
  especially if there were differences between their wealth and class."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.168590Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-war-little-impact-ireland
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The war had very little impact on Ireland."@en ;
  curric:correction """Irish calls for independence were delayed by the outbreak of war, and then
  further delayed in 1918."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.168643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-british-army-went-war-confidently
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The British army went into the war confidently, with a large number of
  troops."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The British army had no more than 700 000 men in August 1914, they would need
  to use mass recruitment and colonial armies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.168649Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-possible-view-british-empire-either
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is possible to view the British Empire as either a force for good
  or bad."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The enormity of the British Empire and number of individuals involved means
  that to attach a simple label to the British Empire is an impossible task."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.169214Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-assume-agricultural-revolution-predominantly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students assume the Agricultural Revolution was predominantly facilitated by
  changes in technology."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Farming tech in common use didn't change much. Improvements in agriculture
  occurred mainly because of the use of new farming methods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.169542Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-great-exhibition-located-crystal-palace
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Great Exhibition was located in the Crystal Palace."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Great Exhibition, which became known as the Crystal Palace, was located
  in Hyde Park."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170077Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-indian-jamaican-rebellions-triggered-complete
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Indian and Jamaican rebellions triggered complete change in those
  colonies."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Major changes were introduced after these rebellions although little was
  changed to address the problem of poverty in either Jamaica or India."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170082Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-time-everyone-knew-hitler-tyrant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """At the time, everyone knew Hitler was a tyrant, so appeasement was clearly
  wrong."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The international community was divided. Many wanted to avoid a repeat of
  World War One. Furthermore, many thought that Germany had been treated harshly after WWI,
  and it seemed fair for Germany to take back some of its territory."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170157Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-medieval-people-called-their-social
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Medieval people called their social system 'the feudal system'."@en ;
  curric:correction """In fact, the term feudal system or feudalism did not start to be used until
  the 17th century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170213Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-historians-finished-debating-legacy-british
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Historians have finished debating the legacy of the British Empire."@en ;
  curric:correction """Historians continue to debate the legacy of the British Empire as new
  information emerges."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170554Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-governor-grants-reforms-morant-bay
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Governor Grant's reforms after the Morant Bay Rebellion reduced the problem of
  poverty for Black Jamaicans."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Grant tackled discrimination and other issues but did not provide the
  financial assistance needed to help many Black Jamaicans escape poverty."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170683Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-effects-decolonisation-positive-countries-newly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The effects of decolonisation were positive for countries newly independent
  from the British Empire."""@en ;
  curric:correction """For many newly independent nations, freedom brought many difficulties as well
  as benefits."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170722Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-time-called-conflict-hundred
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "People at the time called the conflict the Hundred Years' War."@en ;
  curric:correction """People at the time would not have known how long the wars were going to last,
  so this name came after the conflict had ended."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170727Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-elizabethan-england-protestant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Everyone in Elizabethan England was Protestant."@en ;
  curric:correction """Protestantism in Elizabethan England was the norm by the end of Elizabeth's
  reign, but England was religiously divided during her reign."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mary-queen-scots-bloody-mary
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mary, Queen of Scots and 'Bloody Mary' were the same person."@en ;
  curric:correction """The two Marys were cousins, not the same person. Mary was a very common name
  at this time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.171091Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-changes-leadership-russia-led-complete
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Changes in the leadership of Russia led to complete change in the country's
  politics."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Both tsarist rule and Communist rule led to severe restrictions on political
  freedoms, including use of secret police to remove opposition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.171208Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
